100
00:06:26,340 --> 00:06:30,611
Rym: So, I can't believe, you know, Friday, all that happened.

101
00:06:30,631 --> 00:06:34,480
Rym: We had more coverage for Friday at PAX than we've had about, I don't know, most conventions we go to.

102
00:06:34,620 --> 00:06:35,924
Scott: And started at 2 o'clock.

103
00:06:36,545 --> 00:06:41,740
Scott: There are conventions we go to at 8am on Friday that have less to say than we had to say about Friday at PAX.

104
00:06:42,480 --> 00:06:44,184
Rym: Saturday, we wake up.

105
00:06:44,826 --> 00:06:47,533
Rym: And, much like Friday, we had plenty of time.

106
00:06:47,593 --> 00:06:49,699
Rym: The con didn't start until 10am.

107
00:06:50,761 --> 00:06:54,969
Scott: I mean, you know, 2pm on Friday is pretty late, you know.

108
00:06:57,072 --> 00:06:58,455
Scott: 10am on Saturday.

109
00:06:58,475 --> 00:07:01,260
Scott: That's earlier than 2, a lot earlier, you know.

110
00:07:01,500 --> 00:07:06,600
Rym: But still, cons we go to, the hotel cons, they usually have stuff starting at like 8 o'clock on Saturday.

111
00:07:06,961 --> 00:07:08,417
Scott: Otakon opens at 7 or 8, right?

112
00:07:08,902 --> 00:07:10,665
Rym: Uh, 9.

113
00:07:10,665 --> 00:07:11,859
Scott: Even so, that's pretty, you know.

114
00:07:12,140 --> 00:07:13,565
Rym: It's weird, all that extra hours.

115
00:07:13,585 --> 00:07:17,560
Rym: Like, everything about PAX is just a little bit off from what I'm used to.

116
00:07:17,800 --> 00:07:20,571
Rym: Most cons I go to, like PAX is just crooked slightly so.

117
00:07:20,993 --> 00:07:22,880
Rym: Yeah, we open at 10, I know everyone else opens at 9.

118
00:07:22,880 --> 00:07:31,640
Scott: By opening at 10, it's like they give you all this time to eat breakfast, and get your shit together, and hang out, and talk, and not do anything.

119
00:07:32,301 --> 00:07:33,553
Scott: It's really weird.

120
00:07:33,775 --> 00:07:34,300
Scott: But it was nice.

121
00:07:35,201 --> 00:07:43,240
Rym: Now, actually Saturday, we spent probably the first time we actually had a chance to really just kinda wander around the con without any goal in mind.

122
00:07:43,380 --> 00:07:45,206
Rym: I mean, there was no event.

123
00:07:45,367 --> 00:07:46,851
Rym: at 10 we wanted to go to.

124
00:07:46,892 --> 00:07:49,480
Rym: We just woke up, wandered over the con, and walked around.

125
00:07:49,760 --> 00:07:52,993
Scott: Well, there actually was the, um, make a strip panel.

126
00:07:53,173 --> 00:07:54,699
Scott: But we didn't make it to make a strip panel.

127
00:07:54,980 --> 00:07:56,788
Rym: Basically, we said, well, we'll see.

128
00:07:57,009 --> 00:07:59,520
Rym: We haven't had to line up for anything really yet to go in.

129
00:07:59,660 --> 00:08:01,064
Rym: So, let's see about this.

130
00:08:01,105 --> 00:08:01,606
Rym: make a strip.

131
00:08:01,626 --> 00:08:06,120
Rym: And let me tell you, the line for the make a strip was frightening.

132
00:08:06,861 --> 00:08:09,980
Rym: It was perhaps the most painful line in the entire convention.

133
00:08:10,240 --> 00:08:14,660
Scott: Yeah, I mean, at the anime conventions, right, the masquerade gets this huge line and fills up the main events.

134
00:08:15,400 --> 00:08:22,020
Scott: At, you know, PAX, they had main events filling events in main events, pretty much the whole con.

135
00:08:22,120 --> 00:08:24,448
Scott: And that was everything most people wanted to do.

136
00:08:24,488 --> 00:08:28,280
Scott: You wanted to go see the Q&As, you wanted to see the keynote, you wanted to see the concerts.

137
00:08:28,882 --> 00:08:31,930
Scott: You know, you wanted to see the make a strip panel, all main events.

138
00:08:32,432 --> 00:08:34,857
Scott: Every day there were at least two main events to go.

139
00:08:34,919 --> 00:08:35,320
Scott: see, right?

140
00:08:36,601 --> 00:08:38,567
Rym: But the make a strip just kind of transcended that.

141
00:08:38,587 --> 00:08:42,780
Rym: I mean, I expected long lines, and we got into the concerts, you know, by the skin of our teeth.

142
00:08:42,900 --> 00:08:48,836
Rym: And we really didn't have to wait in any lines, but there was no way to get into that make a strip for us.

143
00:08:48,897 --> 00:08:50,140
Rym: There was just no way.

144
00:08:50,300 --> 00:08:54,256
Scott: I figure I went to all the main events I wanted to go to, except for the make a strip.

145
00:08:54,376 --> 00:08:55,320
Scott: I made out pretty well.

146
00:08:56,261 --> 00:09:01,660
Scott: I was expecting, I was thinking I was going to be lucky going to one of them because of the insane lines required.

147
00:09:02,182 --> 00:09:04,159
Scott: But I went to all of them but once, that's pretty good.

148
00:09:04,520 --> 00:09:06,486
Rym: Yep, so pretty much we just kind of wandered around the con.

149
00:09:06,547 --> 00:09:19,120
Rym: Now the thing that was really kind of cool was that because the convention center is really tall, there was basically this kind of long, upward angled throughfare where you'd go up escalator, escalator, escalator to all these different levels.

150
00:09:19,560 --> 00:09:23,000
Rym: And then around on the corner on the other side there was the same thing kind of going back down.

151
00:09:23,040 --> 00:09:29,100
Scott: Yeah, there was like a north lobby, there was like a north end of the convention center and a south end, and they were almost separate convention centers.

152
00:09:29,541 --> 00:09:35,280
Scott: Like, to get from one to the other was like woooo, and then it started like the dark world and the light world almost.

153
00:09:36,222 --> 00:09:40,700
Scott: And each side had a tower of escalators going up and down on multiple floors.

154
00:09:41,060 --> 00:09:49,460
Rym: And this is really why I think why so many people could be at PAX and yet it didn't feel nearly as crowded as like Katsucon or Otakon or even ConnectiCon.

155
00:09:49,741 --> 00:09:57,280
Rym: Well, Saturday, ConnectiCon, is that there was so much space associated with the con that just happened to be there.

156
00:09:57,460 --> 00:10:01,251
Rym: Like, pretty much the whole ground floor, there was nothing con down there at all.

157
00:10:01,312 --> 00:10:04,100
Rym: It was just like restaurants and the big mall area.

158
00:10:04,380 --> 00:10:09,380
Rym: And the thing is, that was all effectively, as far as PAX was concerned, convention space.

159
00:10:09,520 --> 00:10:12,740
Rym: If the con was just going on down there, even though PAX had nothing to do with it.

160
00:10:13,141 --> 00:10:19,340
Scott: Yeah, it's just people all over the building, no matter what part of the building it was, except for the one part where there was another convention.

161
00:10:19,880 --> 00:10:22,306
Rym: And there was just this constant stream of people.

162
00:10:24,050 --> 00:10:28,260
Rym: It's kind of like every counter, people are walking, but there were just so many people going up and down.

163
00:10:28,441 --> 00:10:30,200
Rym: The escalators were just a sea of people.

164
00:10:30,461 --> 00:10:32,079
Scott: And the escalators worked the whole time.

165
00:10:32,501 --> 00:10:33,056
Rym: I can't believe that.

166
00:10:33,200 --> 00:10:34,220
Rym: They never broke at all.

167
00:10:34,340 --> 00:10:35,519
Rym: I'm trying to figure out why.

168
00:10:35,740 --> 00:10:37,066
Scott: Because they're modern escalators.

169
00:10:37,146 --> 00:10:39,154
Scott: Things in the west are new, things in the east are old.

170
00:10:39,174 --> 00:10:40,560
Scott: You know when our escalators were made?

171
00:10:40,701 --> 00:10:44,800
Rym: Actually, they were all rebuilt not that long ago, at the BCC at least.

172
00:10:45,380 --> 00:10:47,339
Scott: East coast escalator repairmen suck, that's all I got to say.

173
00:10:47,620 --> 00:10:48,846
Rym: I think there's a little bit more to it.

174
00:10:49,007 --> 00:10:52,380
Rym: I think the crowd and the dynamic of... Not bad?

175
00:10:52,980 --> 00:10:54,331
Rym: No, definitely not bad.

176
00:10:56,100 --> 00:11:04,320
Rym: I think what it is, is that anime conventions in general seem to have people move around more than they did at PAX.

177
00:11:04,480 --> 00:11:08,420
Rym: Because there are more events going on all over the place at different times.

178
00:11:09,062 --> 00:11:13,880
Rym: And at the same time, for many people, depending on what you're into, less to do at any given point.

179
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:16,740
Rym: So people tend to walk around and walk back and forth a lot.

180
00:11:16,860 --> 00:11:21,080
Rym: But here at PAX, everyone who was walking was on their way somewhere.

181
00:11:21,562 --> 00:11:23,959
Rym: And then when they got there, they stopped and did something.

182
00:11:25,403 --> 00:11:27,880
Rym: You didn't see a lot of people just wandering aimlessly.

183
00:11:28,040 --> 00:11:32,520
Scott: Yeah, a lot of people at Rookon wander aimlessly to look at cosplay or to be in cosplay.

184
00:11:32,802 --> 00:11:35,000
Scott: And I do think that cosplay has a lot to do with it.

185
00:11:35,040 --> 00:11:35,767
Rym: Yeah, that's the other thing.

186
00:11:35,807 --> 00:11:37,100
Rym: Remember, no cosplayers.

187
00:11:37,181 --> 00:11:38,389
Rym: There were plenty of cosplayers.

188
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:40,102
Rym: No, no.

189
00:11:40,122 --> 00:11:41,440
Rym: There was effectively no cosplay.

190
00:11:41,580 --> 00:11:45,180
Rym: In that, when you were just walking around, there was no one getting in your way taking pictures.

191
00:11:45,681 --> 00:11:47,776
Rym: No one would stop and go, "Oh my god, look at that

192
00:11:47,817 --> 00:11:48,280
Rym: cosplay.".

193
00:11:48,320 --> 00:11:50,219
Rym: So as a result, the crowd just moved.

194
00:11:50,460 --> 00:11:51,933
Scott: Yeah, there were people in costume.

195
00:11:52,094 --> 00:11:52,740
Scott: Plenty of them.

196
00:11:52,860 --> 00:11:54,100
Scott: It wasn't the majority.

197
00:11:54,842 --> 00:11:55,927
Rym: It wasn't even the minority.

198
00:11:55,947 --> 00:11:56,309
Rym: It was like 5%.

199
00:11:56,309 --> 00:11:56,630
Rym: Maybe.

200
00:11:56,690 --> 00:11:57,032
Rym: Not even.

201
00:11:59,020 --> 00:12:02,220
Scott: If you looked around at any given point in time, you would see one or two costumes.

202
00:12:03,061 --> 00:12:05,458
Scott: Depending on where you were and how many people were around at the time.

203
00:12:05,981 --> 00:12:10,860
Rym: I use that term loosely because a lot of the costumes were basically just a guy in a Captain Hammer t-shirt.

204
00:12:11,782 --> 00:12:15,013
Scott: Yeah, but the costumes never got in the way.

205
00:12:15,073 --> 00:12:17,060
Scott: The cosplay had no effect on the con.

206
00:12:19,343 --> 00:12:22,500
Scott: None of the things that cosplay does to a convention were happening.

207
00:12:22,700 --> 00:12:25,080
Rym: But I think part of that was just because there was so little cosplay.

208
00:12:25,741 --> 00:12:33,720
Rym: If there had been a ton of people in costume and an equal number of people trying to take pictures of people, then PAX would have ground to a grinding, blistering, horrible halt.

209
00:12:33,980 --> 00:12:34,194
Scott: Probably.

210
00:12:34,801 --> 00:12:41,540
Rym: But there wasn't really, despite all these space that held people, there weren't that many places to go.

211
00:12:41,700 --> 00:12:45,900
Rym: It seems like there were a small number of high quality places to be at any given point.

212
00:12:46,500 --> 00:12:47,649
Scott: Yeah, I mean, where could you go?

213
00:12:47,669 --> 00:12:49,040
Scott: You go to main events, right?

214
00:12:49,320 --> 00:12:50,405
Scott: You can go to the exhibition hall.

215
00:12:50,847 --> 00:12:52,032
Scott: You can go to the PC room.

216
00:12:52,052 --> 00:12:53,799
Scott: You can go to the console rooms.

217
00:12:54,281 --> 00:12:56,369
Scott: You can go to one of the four tiny panel rooms.

218
00:12:56,389 --> 00:12:57,494
Scott: You can go to the annex.

219
00:12:57,955 --> 00:12:59,060
Scott: You can go to the DS lounge.

220
00:12:59,720 --> 00:13:03,660
Rym: Oh, don't forget, in the annex, on the third floor, we were mystified by this.

221
00:13:03,720 --> 00:13:06,860
Rym: Remember, on level three, there's the Serpent Theatre.

222
00:13:07,380 --> 00:13:09,980
Rym: And right next to it was the mystery space.

223
00:13:11,060 --> 00:13:12,260
Scott: You want to talk about the mystery space?

224
00:13:12,360 --> 00:13:13,388
Rym: We talked about it on the other show.

225
00:13:13,408 --> 00:13:18,560
Rym: It was actually just kind of this lame... It wasn't really that lame, but it was a marketing ploy by someone.

226
00:13:18,880 --> 00:13:25,120
Rym: You go and do these puzzles, and there was a guy chained up who looked like Jesus, answered like riddles and all these mini games.

227
00:13:25,924 --> 00:13:27,379
Rym: A lot of the little kids were hanging out there.

228
00:13:27,880 --> 00:13:28,568
Scott: Yeah, it was alright.

229
00:13:28,609 --> 00:13:29,580
Scott: You know, that kind of thing.

230
00:13:30,001 --> 00:13:32,500
Scott: If I was five years younger, that thing would have been awesome.

231
00:13:32,881 --> 00:13:39,380
Rym: Well, the thing is, at the same time, I would have turned the mystery space into an idea we had that we're probably not going to talk about this show.

232
00:13:39,984 --> 00:13:40,071
Scott: Yeah.

233
00:13:40,922 --> 00:13:41,607
Rym: We have an idea.

234
00:13:41,627 --> 00:13:43,380
Rym: There's one thing that was lacking from PAX.

235
00:13:43,500 --> 00:13:46,380
Rym: If you can't figure it out, you'll find out in a future episode.

236
00:13:47,460 --> 00:13:53,640
Rym: But, you know, we got all these places, and we decided, alright, let's go check out every possible thing.

237
00:13:54,120 --> 00:13:58,640
Rym: So we actually went over to the console free play area, which is something I never do at gaming cons.

238
00:13:59,282 --> 00:14:06,580
Rym: For some reason, I just have no desire, when I'm at a gaming con, to walk into a room with a bunch of consoles and play Smash Brothers, which seems like that's what most people do.

239
00:14:06,800 --> 00:14:08,671
Scott: Yeah, it's like, I can play Smash Brothers at home.

240
00:14:08,691 --> 00:14:09,556
Scott: I have friends.

241
00:14:09,637 --> 00:14:10,220
Scott: I own the game.

242
00:14:10,320 --> 00:14:14,840
Scott: Why do I want to spend my precious convention time playing it against people ten thousand times better than me?

243
00:14:15,681 --> 00:14:17,048
Scott: And I know I'm not going to build it.

244
00:14:17,088 --> 00:14:19,340
Scott: It's not, you know, it's like, I'm not one of those people who does it.

245
00:14:19,400 --> 00:14:23,060
Scott: Some people don't want to play against someone better than them because they don't like to lose.

246
00:14:23,641 --> 00:14:27,780
Scott: I don't like to play against people that much better than me because there's no way I can build skill.

247
00:14:27,900 --> 00:14:29,025
Scott: I just die immediately.

248
00:14:29,326 --> 00:14:32,840
Scott: If there was a way I could get better by sitting there and playing and playing and playing, I'd do it.

249
00:14:33,201 --> 00:14:36,840
Scott: But I can't, mostly because you can't just keep sitting there and playing and playing.

250
00:14:36,920 --> 00:14:42,940
Scott: It's loser walks at a convention, you know, because everyone's trying to get more people want time on the machine than there is time on the machine.

251
00:14:43,081 --> 00:14:45,440
Scott: So I don't tend to do those sorts of things.

252
00:14:45,700 --> 00:14:54,180
Rym: Well, part of it, too, is that you walk into any average, you know, gaming room, and there's pretty much, there's like the consoles with the right games that just, there's a line and people playing them constantly.

253
00:14:54,722 --> 00:14:57,836
Rym: And then there's always the other consoles with games people don't really care that much about.

254
00:14:57,876 --> 00:14:58,800
Rym: They just kind of sit there.

255
00:14:59,360 --> 00:15:01,670
Rym: One guy walks up, plays for like two minutes, walks away.

256
00:15:01,710 --> 00:15:04,020
Rym: Someone else walks up, like pokes at it, walks away.

257
00:15:05,020 --> 00:15:09,020
Rym: PAX, once again, has transcended and they did something that I never really see.

258
00:15:09,420 --> 00:15:15,500
Scott: Well, first of all, I was amazed that the console free play rooms, there were a bunch of them, right, on two different floors, I think.

259
00:15:15,861 --> 00:15:17,385
Scott: But they were very, very small.

260
00:15:17,466 --> 00:15:22,220
Scott: I think if you took them all and put them in one room, it would have been smaller than Otakon's video game room.

261
00:15:22,340 --> 00:15:25,631
Rym: By far, Otakon has ten times the console gaming of PAX.

262
00:15:28,760 --> 00:15:29,864
Scott: Yeah, it was crazy.

263
00:15:30,426 --> 00:15:34,120
Scott: I mean, KatsuKon has a lot more console gaming than PAX.

264
00:15:34,620 --> 00:15:43,279
Rym: But yet, you know, you finally walk into these to see what the deal is, and I noticed that any console that's not being played, there's not only no one at it, there's no game in it.

265
00:15:43,880 --> 00:15:54,120
Rym: So we realized that what they've done is you go to a table, you check out a game, and then you get friends, and you go play that game with your friends, and when you're done, you take the game back.

266
00:15:54,780 --> 00:15:54,850
Scott: Yep.

267
00:15:55,540 --> 00:15:55,860
Rym: Brilliant!

268
00:15:56,340 --> 00:15:57,041
Scott: It was brilliant.

269
00:15:57,362 --> 00:16:07,220
Scott: And the thing is, the result was that all the rooms where you could check out a game were pretty quiet because no one who didn't have a game checked out was in there, looking around, walking around.

270
00:16:07,641 --> 00:16:11,060
Scott: All the people who didn't have a game yet were in the "get a game" room.

271
00:16:11,160 --> 00:16:11,556
Rym: Yeah, the LFGs.

272
00:16:12,382 --> 00:16:16,660
Scott: Yeah, there were two LFGs, and the LFGs- Yeah, were there three?

273
00:16:16,800 --> 00:16:17,319
Rym: There were three.

274
00:16:17,520 --> 00:16:31,260
Scott: Okay, there were three LFGs, and there were a lot of people in the LFGs, because in there, they sort of did the normal thing, where they had, you know, eight TVs, you know, with games already on them, running all the time, that you could play while you waited for the game you wanted to become available.

275
00:16:31,420 --> 00:16:40,817
Scott: You know, those rooms are a little bit crowded, but pretty much everyone in there was not playing those games because they wanted to play them, but because they were playing them to wait for the game.

276
00:16:40,857 --> 00:16:42,540
Scott: they actually wanted in their number to be called.

277
00:16:43,082 --> 00:16:45,700
Scott: And, you know, I heard that the number calling went a little slowly.

278
00:16:46,600 --> 00:16:58,120
Scott: You know, some people waited, you know, a half hour, maybe an hour for it to actually have their number called after they said what game they wanted, you know, but they think they put a half hour limit on people playing in the console rooms and such.

279
00:16:58,240 --> 00:17:11,740
Scott: So, you know, they pretty much, you know, move people as quickly as they could, you know, pretty well every console and every one of the console free play rooms is being used all the time, at least that any, as long as someone was wanting to use it.

280
00:17:12,361 --> 00:17:20,000
Scott: And that was it, you know, not if everyone at the con wanted to play a console, it wouldn't have worked, but not everyone wanted to play.

281
00:17:20,200 --> 00:17:28,700
Rym: But just this idea of check out a game, it's kind of like the board game area, which at most cons they do this, where you check out a board game that you want to play and get people to play it with you.

282
00:17:28,880 --> 00:17:38,180
Rym: So there was this, the culture was just completely different and it was more a vehicle to meet cool people and hang out with them than it was a vehicle to see who's the best of Smash Brothers.

283
00:17:38,300 --> 00:17:38,501
Rym: Yeah.

284
00:17:38,801 --> 00:17:49,300
Scott: And the other cool thing about it was like, you could go and if like, if you met someone at the con and you were like, hey, you know, want to play some of this, you could just play some of that no matter what that was.

285
00:17:49,721 --> 00:17:50,807
Scott: Pretty much no matter what that was.

286
00:17:50,827 --> 00:17:53,080
Scott: I mean, I think they obviously didn't have every video game ever.

287
00:17:53,300 --> 00:18:01,040
Rym: No matter what that was, because, you know, they had like the five or whatever console rooms on one floor, but on the other floor they had the two special free play rooms.

288
00:18:01,541 --> 00:18:02,886
Rym: One of them was the leaderboard room.

289
00:18:02,906 --> 00:18:05,696
Rym: They actually kept track of who was winning all these games.

290
00:18:05,716 --> 00:18:06,720
Rym: There's this giant leaderboard.

291
00:18:06,720 --> 00:18:07,943
Scott: You could win prizes, couldn't you?

292
00:18:07,963 --> 00:18:08,625
Scott: I don't know.

293
00:18:08,645 --> 00:18:09,608
Rym: I didn't even pay attention to that.

294
00:18:09,628 --> 00:18:11,713
Scott: I never went in the leaderboard room, but there was.

295
00:18:11,754 --> 00:18:14,160
Rym: no, it existed, but they had big monitors and they were keeping track.

296
00:18:14,220 --> 00:18:14,862
Rym: It was really cool.

297
00:18:14,882 --> 00:18:17,528
Rym: But they also had the classic console room.

298
00:18:17,568 --> 00:18:17,748
Scott: Yes.

299
00:18:17,989 --> 00:18:19,031
Scott: Who was running that room?

300
00:18:19,593 --> 00:18:20,635
Rym: I don't know, but it was right.

301
00:18:20,675 --> 00:18:22,720
Scott: They had a sign run by so-and-so sorry.

302
00:18:22,860 --> 00:18:32,855
Scott: So-and-so I forgot who you were, but what they did is they actually had hours on Friday and their hours and Friday were less than the hours of the con and their hours and Saturday also looked to be relative,

303
00:18:32,875 --> 00:18:36,440
Rym: but it was crossed out in marker and rewritten until 2 a.m

304
00:18:36,560 --> 00:18:45,637
Scott: And it exactly, they decided that they were so awesome that on Saturday they were going to forego their original plan of doing weak ass hours and do kick ass hours instead.

305
00:18:45,917 --> 00:18:47,440
Scott: So mad props to those guys.

306
00:18:47,760 --> 00:18:49,843
Rym: So Scott says, Hey, I wonder if they have kaboom.

307
00:18:49,883 --> 00:18:52,286
Rym: And I said, there's no fucking way they have kaboom.

308
00:18:52,567 --> 00:18:56,732
Rym: So we walk up there and you know, we were looking around and we see all these old consoles.

309
00:18:56,992 --> 00:18:58,895
Rym: I mean, when they said classic, it was classic.

310
00:19:02,840 --> 00:19:04,944
Rym: It was like every console you would have wanted to play.

311
00:19:04,964 --> 00:19:10,173
Rym: I can say one thing, that room seemed more popular on average than the other rooms.

312
00:19:10,373 --> 00:19:14,160
Scott: Well, cause I think it was a little easier in the other rooms, you know, you had less waiting.

313
00:19:14,780 --> 00:19:22,290
Rym: Well, no, I think it's more that older games, a lot of those competitive old, like NES games are much more conducive to quick pickup competitive play.

314
00:19:22,951 --> 00:19:29,300
Scott: Also that, you know, uh, those are games that you can't just play at home easily if you're some noob kid and you're not old school.

315
00:19:29,300 --> 00:19:29,460
Scott: Yeah.

316
00:19:29,480 --> 00:19:32,345
Rym: I mean, NES roms easy, but some of that stuff, not so easy.

317
00:19:32,445 --> 00:19:36,831
Scott: I mean, if you just had an Atari Jaguar, I'd say Katsu Kan, he just put it there with a game in it.

318
00:19:37,252 --> 00:19:38,954
Scott: People would play it a lot just for the novel.

319
00:19:39,095 --> 00:19:39,515
Rym: We did that.

320
00:19:39,555 --> 00:19:40,737
Rym: We brought my Atari 7,800 to Katsu Kan last year.

321
00:19:42,840 --> 00:19:48,806
Rym: We put it up to this gigantic flat screen TV, and there were people like in awe of it.

322
00:19:49,106 --> 00:19:51,369
Rym: We had an ET tournament as a result.

323
00:19:51,549 --> 00:19:51,749
Rym: Yeah.

324
00:19:51,789 --> 00:19:58,335
Rym: But, uh, so we're walking around and we look in the corner and sure enough, there's the Atari 2,600.

325
00:19:58,335 --> 00:20:00,077
Rym: Kaboom is in it.

326
00:20:00,438 --> 00:20:02,960
Rym: And there's a bunch of people playing it and yelling at each other.

327
00:20:03,040 --> 00:20:05,702
Scott: The only Atari 2,600, at least the only one I saw.

328
00:20:06,082 --> 00:20:06,743
Rym: What are the odds?

329
00:20:06,943 --> 00:20:09,745
Scott: So of course I walk over the moment we walk in there too.

330
00:20:09,785 --> 00:20:11,326
Scott: Those guys weren't in there the whole con.

331
00:20:11,346 --> 00:20:13,687
Scott: They were there at the time we walked in there.

332
00:20:13,887 --> 00:20:16,589
Scott: The only time we walked in there looking for Kaboom.

333
00:20:16,809 --> 00:20:19,411
Scott: The Kaboom guys happened to be there at that time.

334
00:20:19,431 --> 00:20:22,653
Rym: Kaboom is not a well known and popular game.

335
00:20:22,773 --> 00:20:26,956
Scott: It's well known and popular, but it's not at the top of the list.

336
00:20:27,016 --> 00:20:29,578
Scott: It's like, you know, second or third tier of old school.

337
00:20:29,638 --> 00:20:32,420
Rym: It's one of those games where people will meet and they'll be like you Kaboom.

338
00:20:33,201 --> 00:20:34,001
Rym: I Kaboom too.

339
00:20:34,281 --> 00:20:35,362
Rym: Let's Kaboom together.

340
00:20:35,682 --> 00:20:37,924
Scott: So, of course, likes to Kaboom with you.

341
00:20:37,944 --> 00:20:38,725
Rym: Oh my God.

342
00:20:39,365 --> 00:20:42,188
Rym: So I walk over there and I'm like, I see you guys are playing Kaboom.

343
00:20:42,208 --> 00:20:43,989
Rym: And they're like, yeah, yeah, we are.

344
00:20:44,309 --> 00:20:47,932
Rym: And I'm like, I don't think you understand how fucking good I am at Kaboom.

345
00:20:48,292 --> 00:20:53,476
Rym: And they all go and they look at the one guy and they're like, I don't think you understand how good this guy is.

346
00:20:53,696 --> 00:20:55,057
Rym: And the guy's like, what's your highest score?

347
00:20:55,338 --> 00:20:56,018
Rym: And I'm like 90,000 something.

348
00:20:56,058 --> 00:20:56,619
Rym: He's like 100,000 something.

349
00:20:58,921 --> 00:21:00,425
Rym: And we kind of stare each other down.

350
00:21:00,745 --> 00:21:02,068
Rym: And I'm about ready to throw down.

351
00:21:02,088 --> 00:21:03,391
Rym: This is going to be like the best thing ever.

352
00:21:03,732 --> 00:21:05,336
Rym: And he says, we can't play.

353
00:21:05,356 --> 00:21:07,180
Rym: These paddles are broken.

354
00:21:08,740 --> 00:21:10,143
Scott: That's pretty typical for an Atari 2600.

355
00:21:10,143 --> 00:21:12,226
Rym: This is the third set we've tried.

356
00:21:12,266 --> 00:21:13,328
Rym: There aren't any more.

357
00:21:13,869 --> 00:21:17,736
Rym: And I say, then he's like, you want to play anyway?

358
00:21:17,756 --> 00:21:19,459
Rym: And I'm like, how broken are they?

359
00:21:19,479 --> 00:21:20,140
Rym: He's like, you'll see.

360
00:21:21,184 --> 00:21:22,600
Scott: Were they more broken than ours?

361
00:21:23,140 --> 00:21:26,427
Rym: Let me put it this way, cause Scott watched this epic battle.

362
00:21:26,527 --> 00:21:27,369
Rym: I was player two.

363
00:21:27,890 --> 00:21:28,873
Rym: He was player one.

364
00:21:29,514 --> 00:21:32,240
Rym: I've been known to play Kaboom for like a half hour straight.

365
00:21:32,860 --> 00:21:40,220
Rym: And this guy might have even been better than me because his absolute high score was a little bit higher than my absolute high score.

366
00:21:40,260 --> 00:21:42,840
Scott: I think his high score was way higher than yours if I remember.

367
00:21:42,840 --> 00:21:43,142
Scott: 10,000 more?

368
00:21:44,160 --> 00:21:45,188
Scott: No, I think it was a lot more.

369
00:21:45,228 --> 00:21:45,813
Scott: I don't remember.

370
00:21:46,498 --> 00:21:46,800
Scott: Anyway.

371
00:21:47,281 --> 00:21:50,489
Rym: Anyway, so he got like 130 and I got like 150.

372
00:21:50,489 --> 00:21:51,391
Rym: They were so broken.

373
00:21:55,600 --> 00:21:58,172
Scott: We really need to get some like Atari 2600 controllers in the box.

374
00:21:59,920 --> 00:22:01,443
Rym: It was so sad.

375
00:22:01,503 --> 00:22:07,553
Rym: It was like watching Wayne Gretzky play hockey against Wayne Gretzky, but he was given a one inch.

376
00:22:07,593 --> 00:22:11,760
Rym: They were both given one inch long sticks and the net was smaller than the puck.

377
00:22:13,624 --> 00:22:14,999
Rym: Yeah, that's basically what it felt like.

378
00:22:15,220 --> 00:22:15,858
Scott: It was real sad.

379
00:22:16,060 --> 00:22:25,480
Rym: But at least I shook hands with the only person I've ever met in my entire life, other than my father, who had a chance of beating me at Kaboom.

380
00:22:25,620 --> 00:22:26,843
Rym: I was excited.

381
00:22:26,863 --> 00:22:28,306
Rym: I didn't have a business card.

382
00:22:28,346 --> 00:22:32,976
Rym: So Kaboom guy, if you happen to hear this at all, drop me a line.

383
00:22:33,036 --> 00:22:34,680
Rym: I will totally make sure we have a tournament.

384
00:22:35,200 --> 00:22:41,397
Scott: Some I see on eBay, this guy claims Atari 2600, quote, jitter free paddles.

385
00:22:41,938 --> 00:22:42,680
Scott: Work fab.

386
00:22:42,881 --> 00:22:43,985
Scott: Oh, whatever.

387
00:22:44,085 --> 00:22:46,554
Rym: I figured out I actually cracked open a third party once.

388
00:22:46,594 --> 00:22:47,517
Rym: I'm just going to buff that thing.

389
00:22:47,537 --> 00:22:48,300
Rym: I think it'll work fine.

390
00:22:48,460 --> 00:22:48,962
Scott: Here's another people.

391
00:22:49,043 --> 00:22:50,348
Scott: New set of paddles.

392
00:22:50,609 --> 00:22:51,272
Scott: Right.

393
00:22:51,353 --> 00:22:52,919
Scott: New, they say in box.

394
00:22:53,420 --> 00:22:55,684
Rym: But just think about the magic of packs.

395
00:22:56,345 --> 00:23:06,960
Rym: What are the odds that I ran into the one awesome dude at Kaboom and his posse of shit talking friends when I am ready with my shit talking friends to bust out some Kaboom?

396
00:23:07,723 --> 00:23:08,727
Scott: Yeah, it's good times.

397
00:23:09,610 --> 00:23:11,960
Scott: If only Mega Man 2 was competitive.

398
00:23:12,941 --> 00:23:15,161
Rym: We should make competitive Mega Man 2.

399
00:23:15,161 --> 00:23:15,467
Scott: We should.

400
00:23:15,671 --> 00:23:16,019
Scott: All right.

401
00:23:16,780 --> 00:23:22,680
Rym: So I want to take a point because I said the serpent theater and, you know, our panel was in the Wolfman theater.

402
00:23:23,641 --> 00:23:27,856
Rym: The theaters all had names, the Wolfman, the serpent, the.

403
00:23:27,916 --> 00:23:29,080
Rym: I don't remember what the other ones were.

404
00:23:29,100 --> 00:23:29,561
Scott: I got him.

405
00:23:29,581 --> 00:23:30,242
Scott: Give me a second.

406
00:23:31,245 --> 00:23:38,380
Scott: The raven and the serpent walrus, raven walrus, serpent Wolfman.

407
00:23:38,861 --> 00:23:43,900
Rym: So, you know, I was curious about that because when we originally got our letter about, hey, you guys are going to do this panel.

408
00:23:44,542 --> 00:23:46,834
