00:36:02,242 --> 00:36:02,383
Scott: Yeah.

614
00:36:02,403 --> 00:36:04,091
Scott: And basically these bubbles appear.

615
00:36:04,112 --> 00:36:05,820
Scott: And if you go in the bubble, you're invincible.

616
00:36:05,920 --> 00:36:11,520
Scott: So the basic idea with the game was go in the bubble, the bubble shrinking, get out of it before it kills you.

617
00:36:12,081 --> 00:36:18,920
Scott: Go to another bubble that just opened up without dying on your way there and shoot as many bad guys as possible to get lots of points.

618
00:36:19,060 --> 00:36:21,600
Rym: Now, let me tell you, because obviously they'd all practiced.

619
00:36:22,182 --> 00:36:24,820
Rym: That was some epic Geometry Wars play like it.

620
00:36:25,281 --> 00:36:26,124
Rym: There is nothing great.

621
00:36:26,144 --> 00:36:31,160
Scott: You know, when the audience is watching a game and they go, oh, there was a lot of O's going on.

622
00:36:31,520 --> 00:36:38,080
Rym: In video gaming, then playing or spectating among incredibly skilled players at a game.

623
00:36:38,140 --> 00:36:42,200
Rym: If there are four people who are similarly skilled at a game of skill.

624
00:36:42,880 --> 00:36:44,939
Rym: Well, I guess you couldn't be skilled at a game of chance.

625
00:36:45,941 --> 00:36:50,460
Rym: And they are competing against each other and there's an audience who is knowledgeable about the game.

626
00:36:51,082 --> 00:36:53,180
Rym: That is some really good entertainment right there.

627
00:36:53,240 --> 00:36:56,380
Scott: Well, I mean, not everyone playing was as good as all the other guys.

628
00:36:56,540 --> 00:36:59,380
Scott: There were, you know, clearly some people were better at the Geometry Wars than others.

629
00:36:59,440 --> 00:37:01,360
Scott: I got to say this, but they're all better than me.

630
00:37:01,600 --> 00:37:04,756
Rym: In the game we watched, the player who was yellow, that was some crazy.

631
00:37:04,836 --> 00:37:05,560
Rym: Oh, my God.

632
00:37:05,700 --> 00:37:07,257
Scott: Yeah, yellow pulled off this crazy crazy.

633
00:37:07,820 --> 00:37:08,684
Rym: Yellow is going to die.

634
00:37:08,744 --> 00:37:09,247
Rym: Holy shit.

635
00:37:09,267 --> 00:37:09,649
Rym: Yellow just.

636
00:37:09,809 --> 00:37:10,251
Rym: Oh, my God.

637
00:37:10,271 --> 00:37:10,653
Rym: Yellow is good.

638
00:37:10,734 --> 00:37:11,236
Rym: Oh, my God.

639
00:37:11,256 --> 00:37:12,080
Rym: Yellow just avoided that.

640
00:37:12,400 --> 00:37:15,480
Rym: Like yellow would be in the corner surrounded by bad guys about to die.

641
00:37:15,940 --> 00:37:17,208
Rym: Suddenly everyone else is dead.

642
00:37:17,248 --> 00:37:19,420
Scott: Yellow's left and yellow's left in a bubble.

643
00:37:19,541 --> 00:37:22,059
Scott: And it's like, oh, it's all right.

644
00:37:22,541 --> 00:37:23,043
Rym: Yeah.

645
00:37:23,063 --> 00:37:27,560
Rym: If you don't do other things at PAX, the Omega-thons, especially the later rounds.

646
00:37:27,921 --> 00:37:29,471
Scott: It's worth your time to go.

647
00:37:29,491 --> 00:37:30,780
Rym: Totally worth it.

648
00:37:30,880 --> 00:37:32,700
Scott: I imagine I didn't go to the Jenga round.

649
00:37:32,880 --> 00:37:35,099
Scott: I imagine the Jenga round would have been mad intense.

650
00:37:35,680 --> 00:37:37,896
Scott: Just watching these people thinking it's going to fall, man.

651
00:37:37,936 --> 00:37:38,178
Scott: Oh, man.

652
00:37:38,218 --> 00:37:38,419
Rym: Oh, man.

653
00:37:38,600 --> 00:37:42,880
Rym: So I point out at this point that we had not yet been to the exhibition room.

654
00:37:43,200 --> 00:37:43,381
Scott: All right.

655
00:37:43,402 --> 00:37:46,360
Scott: Now, the exhibition room at PAX is much fabled.

656
00:37:46,580 --> 00:37:49,678
Scott: You know, basically people act like it's the new E3.

657
00:37:50,121 --> 00:37:50,462
Scott: It is.

658
00:37:50,643 --> 00:37:51,527
Rym: It is the new E3.

659
00:37:51,567 --> 00:37:51,788
Scott: Yes.

660
00:37:51,849 --> 00:37:54,300
Scott: But, you know, they act like it's this gigantic room.

661
00:37:54,602 --> 00:37:57,439
Scott: You get all the big video game companies are there and they are.

662
00:37:57,761 --> 00:38:00,738
Scott: And they all bring the games that in olden days they would have brought to E3.

663
00:38:01,180 --> 00:38:02,227
Scott: Games that aren't out yet.

664
00:38:02,589 --> 00:38:04,160
Scott: You know, games they really want to sell.

665
00:38:04,320 --> 00:38:05,895
Scott: Big fancy booths, the whole thing.

666
00:38:05,956 --> 00:38:06,319
Scott: And they do.

667
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:11,400
Scott: But really, the exhibition hall was about as big as the New York Comic-Con.

668
00:38:11,500 --> 00:38:14,660
Scott: It wasn't really that big square footage wise.

669
00:38:15,201 --> 00:38:17,260
Scott: You know, I wasn't like impressed by the size.

670
00:38:17,340 --> 00:38:19,680
Scott: I was able to cover the whole room pretty much.

671
00:38:20,001 --> 00:38:26,720
Scott: I wasn't able to play every single game because I would have had to wait in lots of lines at many of the booths and a lot of the games weren't worth playing.

672
00:38:27,200 --> 00:38:28,379
Scott: But I saw every booth.

673
00:38:28,700 --> 00:38:32,200
Rym: But at the same time it was concentrated awesome.

674
00:38:32,420 --> 00:38:34,220
Rym: It wasn't like a dealer's room.

675
00:38:34,400 --> 00:38:39,140
Rym: I mean, the analogy of the exhibition hall to any other con is that's the dealer's room.

676
00:38:39,200 --> 00:38:42,960
Rym: But there weren't actually that many people selling things.

677
00:38:43,020 --> 00:38:44,970
Rym: It was mostly exhibitions.

678
00:38:45,030 --> 00:38:46,638
Rym: It was people showing things off.

679
00:38:47,645 --> 00:38:48,875
Scott: Well, they were advertising.

680
00:38:48,895 --> 00:38:49,600
Scott: They were selling them.

681
00:38:49,680 --> 00:38:51,800
Scott: But they weren't selling them right then and there.

682
00:38:51,940 --> 00:38:56,600
Scott: They were trying to sell you on them so that you would later go to GameStop and buy them.

683
00:38:56,780 --> 00:38:58,840
Rym: Yeah, but the people were actually selling things.

684
00:38:59,100 --> 00:39:01,859
Rym: Like PinkGodzilla was selling some stuff and there was like one...

685
00:39:02,580 --> 00:39:04,119
Scott: Namco was selling their Pac-Man merch.

686
00:39:04,360 --> 00:39:06,940
Rym: There was one anime dealer selling like anime stuff.

687
00:39:07,160 --> 00:39:09,900
Rym: And oh my god, those people rake it in because they were the only people there.

688
00:39:09,940 --> 00:39:11,920
Scott: The people who were selling the retro video game stuff.

689
00:39:13,147 --> 00:39:13,718
Scott: That was about it.

690
00:39:14,061 --> 00:39:16,272
Rym: Yeah, it was mostly Nintendo.

691
00:39:16,353 --> 00:39:17,659
Rym: Play games that aren't out yet.

692
00:39:18,982 --> 00:39:19,789
Rym: Play Fallout.

693
00:39:19,910 --> 00:39:21,060
Rym: Oh my god, play Fallout.

694
00:39:21,540 --> 00:39:22,675
Rym: Play Iron Jeff DS.

695
00:39:23,360 --> 00:39:24,269
Scott: Play Left 4 Dead.

696
00:39:24,350 --> 00:39:25,460
Scott: Oh my god, Left 4 Dead.

697
00:39:26,541 --> 00:39:27,586
Rym: Play Starcraft 2.

698
00:39:27,586 --> 00:39:28,791
Scott: Oh my god, Starcraft 2.

699
00:39:28,791 --> 00:39:30,338
Scott: Play World of Warcraft expansion.

700
00:39:30,358 --> 00:39:30,860
Scott: Oh my god.

701
00:39:31,240 --> 00:39:38,200
Rym: Probably the most sought after booth in this entire exhibition hall I think would have been booth 632.

702
00:39:38,200 --> 00:39:38,976
Rym: The Fallout 3 booth.

703
00:39:39,180 --> 00:39:41,415
Scott: Well, it's either the Fallout booth or the Left 4 Dead booth.

704
00:39:41,455 --> 00:39:42,220
Scott: It's a tough call.

705
00:39:42,522 --> 00:39:42,966
Scott: Tough call.

706
00:39:43,006 --> 00:39:44,580
Scott: They both had long lines the whole time.

707
00:39:44,740 --> 00:39:49,240
Rym: While they had similarly long lines, there were a lot more Fallouts to play.

708
00:39:49,740 --> 00:39:51,620
Rym: So I think there were more people all told.

709
00:39:51,860 --> 00:39:56,940
Rym: And also, the Fallout booth was the only way to get the Fallout puppet.

710
00:39:57,560 --> 00:39:58,799
Scott: Not too many people got it.

711
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:04,140
Rym: Yes, the Fallout puppet was perhaps the greatest status symbol you could have at that con.

712
00:40:04,361 --> 00:40:08,100
Rym: Other than an all access badge or an Omegathon shirt.

713
00:40:08,260 --> 00:40:10,658
Scott: I was going to say, an Omegathon shirt is a pretty big status symbol.

714
00:40:10,960 --> 00:40:13,400
Rym: The puppet was number 3 in terms of standing out in the crowd.

715
00:40:13,860 --> 00:40:14,416
Scott: Pretty much, yeah.

716
00:40:14,880 --> 00:40:17,416
Rym: Well, I guess number 4 was being me and Scott.

717
00:40:17,457 --> 00:40:18,000
Rym: No, just kidding.

718
00:40:18,720 --> 00:40:19,539
Rym: No, not even close.

719
00:40:20,200 --> 00:40:23,620
Scott: No one noticed us at all except for our listeners and people at our panel.

720
00:40:23,920 --> 00:40:25,236
Rym: Yeah, but all the people at the panel.

721
00:40:25,256 --> 00:40:25,600
Rym: But anyway.

722
00:40:25,980 --> 00:40:28,431
Rym: So, the Fallout booth.

723
00:40:28,451 --> 00:40:30,300
Rym: I don't think you understand the tonight.

724
00:40:30,400 --> 00:40:32,240
Rym: There were people in that line.

725
00:40:32,500 --> 00:40:36,580
Rym: There were people lined up well before the exhibition hall opened on all three days.

726
00:40:36,941 --> 00:40:43,280
Rym: To get into the exhibition hall the second it opened in order to line up to then hours later play Fallout 3.

727
00:40:43,280 --> 00:40:44,500
Scott: That's actually not a bad idea.

728
00:40:44,640 --> 00:40:47,760
Scott: Because look, the exhibition hall opens pretty much when the con opens, right?

729
00:40:48,180 --> 00:40:53,620
Scott: So, if you wait in line before the con opens, you're not really losing any con in that line.

730
00:40:54,241 --> 00:40:59,440
Scott: If you are really early in that line and you get to be really early in the Fallout line.

731
00:40:59,821 --> 00:41:02,174
Scott: You could play Fallout at like maybe 10.05, 10.10 in the morning.

732
00:41:03,902 --> 00:41:09,580
Scott: And thus, you won't lose any of your con, any significant portion of it, and you'll get to play Fallout.

733
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:15,060
Scott: If you had tried to go play Fallout at pretty much any other time, you would have to wait for like an hour maybe.

734
00:41:15,260 --> 00:41:16,149
Scott: Half hour to an hour.

735
00:41:16,189 --> 00:41:17,300
Scott: A long, long time.

736
00:41:17,560 --> 00:41:21,580
Scott: You would have lost a significant portion of con time to just play this game.

737
00:41:21,900 --> 00:41:27,360
Scott: So, waiting in line before the con to play Fallout or Left 4 Dead or Starcraft 2 was a pretty good idea.

738
00:41:27,562 --> 00:41:29,119
Scott: And the people doing it were pretty smart.

739
00:41:30,082 --> 00:41:33,100
Scott: I just didn't want to play those games badly enough to wait in those lines.

740
00:41:33,100 --> 00:41:35,980
Rym: But I did want to play them every time I walked into this room.

741
00:41:36,040 --> 00:41:37,580
Rym: I didn't want to play them just that badly.

742
00:41:37,780 --> 00:41:40,273
Rym: But I'd walk into the room and be like, "Oh my god, I want to play Fallout.

743
00:41:40,313 --> 00:41:41,118
Rym: Oh my god, I want to play

744
00:41:41,138 --> 00:41:41,419
Rym: Fallout.".

745
00:41:41,701 --> 00:41:45,860
Rym: And then I'd see the line, and it's bigger than any line I've ever really wanted to stand in in my life.

746
00:41:45,960 --> 00:41:47,833
Scott: Well, it's not that it was physically large.

747
00:41:47,873 --> 00:41:48,860
Scott: I mean, it was pretty large.

748
00:41:48,880 --> 00:41:50,300
Rym: Well, bigger in terms of how long it would take.

749
00:41:50,520 --> 00:41:50,884
Scott: Exactly.

750
00:41:50,904 --> 00:41:52,380
Scott: It's because people are playing a game.

751
00:41:52,420 --> 00:41:52,940
Rym: I'll put it this way.

752
00:41:52,960 --> 00:41:54,819
Scott: And then they stop, and then one person goes and plays.

753
00:41:54,980 --> 00:41:56,605
Rym: It's not even that it would have taken that long.

754
00:41:56,866 --> 00:42:06,960
Rym: It's that the opportunity cost at PAX, what I would have had to ma- I mean, I waited four hours to ride a rollercoaster once, but I wasn't missing anything.

755
00:42:07,480 --> 00:42:09,920
Rym: I was missing other rollercoasters that I'd already ridden.

756
00:42:10,560 --> 00:42:16,260
Rym: At PAX, every second I wasn't doing something, and I was standing in line instead, I was missing something.

757
00:42:16,480 --> 00:42:18,980
Scott: We paid a lot of money to go to Seattle and stay in a hotel.

758
00:42:19,220 --> 00:42:23,240
Scott: You can't waste a single moment of that incredibly short trip that you used all your vacation days on.

759
00:42:23,300 --> 00:42:24,479
Rym: But luckily, I will say this.

760
00:42:24,981 --> 00:42:31,760
Rym: Every single person I talked to who played Fallout was so excited about Fallout that I- Hold on, three by the way.

761
00:42:31,900 --> 00:42:35,620
Rym: Yes, Fallout, not Fallout 1, which was fun when I was young.

762
00:42:35,860 --> 00:42:37,109
Scott: I tried to play it recently.

763
00:42:37,774 --> 00:42:38,660
Scott: Let me tell a little story.

764
00:42:38,760 --> 00:42:43,720
Scott: Fallout 1 is a game I tried to play a long time ago, and then I tried to play it again a year at RIT once.

765
00:42:44,160 --> 00:42:46,600
Scott: And then I tried to play it very, very recently.

766
00:42:47,301 --> 00:42:53,260
Scott: The last time Scott Johnson was over our house, he got it on GameTap for me with his account so I could try it again.

767
00:42:54,541 --> 00:42:58,000
Scott: I did a little better this time, but that is a game that I just cannot play.

768
00:42:58,462 --> 00:43:00,776
Scott: I just completely fail at that game entirely.

769
00:43:02,563 --> 00:43:04,115
Scott: I need someone to really help me.

770
00:43:04,417 --> 00:43:04,760
Scott: I don't know.

771
00:43:05,120 --> 00:43:06,410
Scott: I just can't figure it out.

772
00:43:06,471 --> 00:43:07,680
Scott: I just die immediately.

773
00:43:08,180 --> 00:43:09,367
Scott: I can't figure out where I'm going.

774
00:43:09,427 --> 00:43:10,373
Scott: It's too open-ended.

775
00:43:10,393 --> 00:43:11,640
Scott: It's not my deal.

776
00:43:12,020 --> 00:43:13,933
Scott: Maybe Fallout 3 will be a little better for me.

777
00:43:14,013 --> 00:43:14,940
Scott: Fallout 1 was not.

778
00:43:16,541 --> 00:43:35,680
Rym: But suffice to say, I am real excited about Fallout 3 because I feel like just based on the booth, if the booth is any indication, they know what it was that made Fallout good, and they know what parts of Fallout needed to go away and were just limitations of technology.

779
00:43:35,840 --> 00:43:39,879
Rym: I think the game is going to be amazing, but I reserve judgment until I play it.

780
00:43:40,201 --> 00:43:42,400
Scott: I am more excited about Left 4 Dead.

781
00:43:43,260 --> 00:43:44,385
Scott: Oh man, Left 4 Dead.

782
00:43:44,405 --> 00:43:47,057
Scott: I knew Valve was making a zombie game.

783
00:43:47,097 --> 00:43:47,720
Scott: That's what I knew.

784
00:43:48,040 --> 00:43:50,300
Scott: And I had seen maybe some videos and some screenshots.

785
00:43:51,405 --> 00:44:04,239
Scott: I stood there watching people play a game of Left 4 Dead together, just seeing the people inside the door waiting at the door that they can't close for the final person to get in the door so they can close it.

786
00:44:04,980 --> 00:44:06,520
Scott: That's some good gameplay right there.

787
00:44:06,660 --> 00:44:12,440
Rym: Oh my god, I don't even want to get into it, but we saw game mechanics that made us drool.

788
00:44:14,383 --> 00:44:16,780
Rym: What do zombie first person shooters need to be good?

789
00:44:17,140 --> 00:44:18,840
Rym: They need objectives that don't suck.

790
00:44:18,880 --> 00:44:20,439
Rym: They need zombies coming up to hell right now!

791
00:44:20,840 --> 00:44:21,608
Rym: Prez!

792
00:44:21,628 --> 00:44:21,770
Rym: Prez!

793
00:44:21,911 --> 00:44:22,780
Rym: They killed your parents!

794
00:44:23,780 --> 00:44:25,228
Rym: Oh my god, did this game have that.

795
00:44:25,731 --> 00:44:27,380
Rym: It had everything I want in a zombie game.

796
00:44:27,800 --> 00:44:34,660
Scott: If you have a copy of Steam, and Half Life 2 works on your computer, and you don't buy Left 4 Dead, you're an idiot.

797
00:44:35,060 --> 00:44:40,180
Rym: Because even if it sucks, this is the best chance zombie first person shooters have ever had.

798
00:44:40,862 --> 00:44:42,212
Scott: It's pretty much going to be win.

799
00:44:42,253 --> 00:44:43,220
Scott: I can almost guarantee it.

800
00:44:43,240 --> 00:44:45,900
Rym: And if it isn't, well, I'm going to take that chance.

801
00:44:46,302 --> 00:44:49,560
Scott: There were other games that were big, like Starcraft 2.

802
00:44:49,560 --> 00:44:54,460
Scott: I looked at it a little bit, and I didn't really see enough of it to make any sort of judgement on it.

803
00:44:55,002 --> 00:44:58,060
Scott: I can talk about Starcraft 2 videos that I saw online before the time.

804
00:44:58,080 --> 00:45:02,620
Rym: I can say this, the people in line to play Starcraft 2 were Starcraft people.

805
00:45:03,528 --> 00:45:04,540
Rym: You could look at them and be like "wow".

806
00:45:04,600 --> 00:45:13,520
Scott: I was watching some videos online of Starcraft 2 and some of the things they're changing in it and whatnot, and I was actually starting to feel good about it, because I was like "yeah, yeah, yeah".

807
00:45:13,600 --> 00:45:14,204
Scott: I think so too.

808
00:45:14,244 --> 00:45:27,820
Rym: I feel like Starcraft 2, at least based on what I saw, because I stood over someone's shoulder and watched them play like 10 minutes of it, it might be another instance of knowing what it is that made the original Starcraft popular, and distilling that into modern technology.

809
00:45:28,080 --> 00:45:30,860
Scott: Yeah, well that's all Blizzard does is distill.

810
00:45:31,806 --> 00:45:32,520
Rym: Yes, but again...

811
00:45:33,080 --> 00:45:34,975
Scott: I was reminded recently, there's a good RTS...

812
00:45:36,541 --> 00:45:37,600
Rym: Oh, this is so sad.

813
00:45:37,680 --> 00:45:41,354
Scott: There's an RTS in that bootleg demakes package.

814
00:45:41,374 --> 00:45:43,000
Scott: that's actually a real RTS.

815
00:45:43,141 --> 00:45:44,700
Scott: It's playable and has multiplayer.

816
00:45:44,960 --> 00:45:48,640
Rym: Scott told me about this, but I'll just interject by pointing out that I did check this out, I played it.

817
00:45:49,220 --> 00:45:52,919
Rym: This is pretty much, it is like, I would call it an RTS.

818
00:45:53,360 --> 00:45:57,419
Rym: It is like the most generic, and this is the core of a basic RTS.

819
00:45:57,941 --> 00:45:59,480
Scott: It's a baby RTS, basically.

820
00:46:00,042 --> 00:46:03,420
Scott: I tried to play it, and I was playing it as well as I thought I could play it.

821
00:46:03,800 --> 00:46:09,877
Scott: I tried real hard, real hard, and basically it was "alright, I've built a bunch of ships,

822
00:46:09,977 --> 00:46:10,338
Scott: attack!".

823
00:46:11,121 --> 00:46:15,920
Scott: They have a million times the number of ships I have, they killed me instantly, then they came and attacked me.

824
00:46:16,342 --> 00:46:18,199
Rym: Oh my god, I got a fighter jet, let's go.

825
00:46:18,400 --> 00:46:22,819
Rym: And they've got planets made out of fighter jets just waiting for it.

826
00:46:23,360 --> 00:46:24,938
Scott: I just suck so much at RTSs.

827
00:46:25,260 --> 00:46:28,840
Scott: It's just the building things fast enough, I just can't do it for some reason.

828
00:46:28,840 --> 00:46:32,020
