00:58:12,500 --> 00:58:12,575
Scott: Yep.

1032
00:58:13,565 --> 00:58:14,380
Scott: What else is going on?

1033
00:58:14,962 --> 00:58:18,780
Scott: Oh, there's a booth that sells the PAX merch and all Penny Arcade merch.

1034
00:58:18,900 --> 00:58:20,057
Rym: It was gigantic.

1035
00:58:20,860 --> 00:58:21,940
Scott: Yeah, it was a pretty big booth.

1036
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:24,620
Scott: And there were two lines, so you could go to either side of it.

1037
00:58:25,302 --> 00:58:26,009
Scott: We were stupid.

1038
00:58:26,049 --> 00:58:27,060
Scott: We saw a line for it.

1039
00:58:27,100 --> 00:58:28,053
Scott: We're like, "Yeah, we'll go back

1040
00:58:28,114 --> 00:58:28,398
Scott: later.".

1041
00:58:28,681 --> 00:58:30,860
Scott: We came back later, the PAX shirts were sold out.

1042
00:58:30,920 --> 00:58:31,900
Scott: They sold out of PAX shirts.

1043
00:58:31,900 --> 00:58:32,167
Scott: I was like,

1044
00:58:32,208 --> 00:58:32,475
Scott: "Fuck!".

1045
00:58:32,841 --> 00:58:36,580
Rym: Every single one of them in every size was sold out relatively early.

1046
00:58:36,620 --> 00:58:40,480
Scott: I think that they should just ask your t-shirt size when you get a badge and they should just give one to everybody.

1047
00:58:40,661 --> 00:58:41,760
Rym: Even if they raise the badge price.

1048
00:58:41,840 --> 00:58:43,620
Scott: And raise the price to make everyone pay for one.

1049
00:58:43,942 --> 00:58:44,669
Rym: I'd be fine with that.

1050
00:58:44,690 --> 00:58:45,660
Rym: That'd be pretty cool, actually.

1051
00:58:46,282 --> 00:58:49,040
Rym: And then make pre-registering the only way to get a shirt.

1052
00:58:49,381 --> 00:58:49,720
Scott: Exactly.

1053
00:58:50,140 --> 00:58:50,230
Rym: Yeah.

1054
00:58:51,341 --> 00:58:52,669
Rym: I found Iron Chef DS.

1055
00:58:52,789 --> 00:58:53,332
Rym: I played it.

1056
00:58:53,775 --> 00:58:54,700
Rym: It was kind of okay.

1057
00:58:54,940 --> 00:58:58,120
Scott: It was just Cooking Mama only with an Iron Chef America theme on it.

1058
00:58:58,302 --> 00:58:58,900
Rym: It was kind of fun.

1059
00:58:58,981 --> 00:58:59,719
Scott: I played a little bit.

1060
00:59:00,742 --> 00:59:01,378
Rym: Let me put it this way.

1061
00:59:01,802 --> 00:59:04,700
Rym: It was kind of fun, but the versus mechanic.

1062
00:59:04,961 --> 00:59:08,580
Rym: The mechanic of the game was very, very clever.

1063
00:59:08,740 --> 00:59:09,519
Rym: And I'll leave it at that.

1064
00:59:09,941 --> 00:59:10,122
Scott: Yeah.

1065
00:59:10,142 --> 00:59:12,380
Scott: There was a Red Riding Hood DS game.

1066
00:59:12,460 --> 00:59:13,858
Scott: I don't remember exactly what it was.

1067
00:59:14,683 --> 00:59:15,659
Rym: Was it Kill Zombies?

1068
00:59:16,261 --> 00:59:18,900
Scott: It was like Shoot Zombies, You're Red Riding Hood or some crap.

1069
00:59:19,022 --> 00:59:19,678
Scott: It was fucked up.

1070
00:59:20,303 --> 00:59:22,820
Scott: I tried to play it and I couldn't figure out the controls.

1071
00:59:22,980 --> 00:59:23,978
Scott: They were so screwy.

1072
00:59:24,320 --> 00:59:26,980
Rym: And the person demoing it seemed to know there was a problem.

1073
00:59:27,160 --> 00:59:29,420
Rym: Because apparently a lot of people are having trouble with this.

1074
00:59:29,642 --> 00:59:31,400
Scott: She was like, do you need me to show you how to play?

1075
00:59:31,560 --> 00:59:33,380
Scott: And I'm like, no, I'm going to figure it out.

1076
00:59:34,545 --> 00:59:35,519
Scott: And no, it was not.

1077
00:59:35,821 --> 00:59:36,478
Scott: Don't buy it.

1078
00:59:36,620 --> 00:59:37,060
Scott: Don't bother.

1079
00:59:38,122 --> 00:59:38,937
Scott: Let's see what else is going on.

1080
00:59:39,140 --> 00:59:40,620
Scott: Oh, there's the animal boxing game.

1081
00:59:40,861 --> 00:59:41,074
Scott: All right.

1082
00:59:41,360 --> 00:59:43,760
Rym: Animal boxing is animal boxing.

1083
00:59:43,920 --> 00:59:45,740
Rym: It is humans versus animals.

1084
00:59:46,302 --> 00:59:48,140
Rym: The game is kind of okay for play.

1085
00:59:48,200 --> 00:59:52,079
Rym: Like I didn't play it long enough to say if it's a great game, but I can say one thing.

1086
00:59:52,462 --> 00:59:54,840
Rym: The game gets like 10 points for style.

1087
00:59:55,302 --> 00:59:56,820
Scott: Yeah, it doesn't get any points for play.

1088
00:59:56,981 --> 01:00:01,240
Scott: I basically played it and I vigorously tapped the stylus on the animal and then it eventually fell over.

1089
01:00:01,400 --> 01:00:04,320
Rym: But at the same time, multiplayer against a human might be really fun.

1090
01:00:05,221 --> 01:00:07,820
Rym: There were Rock Band and Guitar Hero.

1091
01:00:08,020 --> 01:00:10,761
Scott: Well, Rock Band 2 and Guitar Hero 4.

1092
01:00:10,761 --> 01:00:11,499
Rym: Yes, obviously.

1093
01:00:12,080 --> 01:00:13,919
Rym: Stages set up, gigantic ones.

1094
01:00:14,380 --> 01:00:17,140
Rym: And like people were basically playing concerts.

1095
01:00:17,360 --> 01:00:23,160
Rym: And while I'm not interested in these games, people were really having a good time with that.

1096
01:00:23,180 --> 01:00:26,179
Scott: If you walked over to them at any point in time, there were people playing them.

1097
01:00:26,320 --> 01:00:32,920
Scott: And from what it seemed to me, it seemed like people liked Rock Band 2 a little bit better than they like Guitar Hero 4.

1098
01:00:32,920 --> 01:00:39,280
Scott: But there was some music in Guitar Hero 4 such as Van Halen that was not in Rock Band that people really liked and would, you know.

1099
01:00:39,901 --> 01:00:45,780
Scott: And actually, you know, Konami is coming out with their, you know, rock whatever, rock revolution or whatever they're calling it.

1100
01:00:45,904 --> 01:00:46,138
Scott: Right.

1101
01:00:46,642 --> 01:00:49,540
Scott: I was actually reading some details about that today on the Internet.

1102
01:00:50,463 --> 01:00:51,960
Scott: And I'll talk about it more later.

1103
01:00:52,081 --> 01:00:56,339
Scott: But it looks like maybe Konami has the right idea and is going to go somewhere.

1104
01:00:57,040 --> 01:01:06,599
Scott: You know, the gods of rhythm games might, you know, we doubted them coming into this plastic instrument zone, you know, given that they had lost, you know, with their guitar freaks back in the day.

1105
01:01:07,064 --> 01:01:08,600
Scott: But I think they might have learned something.

1106
01:01:08,660 --> 01:01:11,100
Scott: And I would watch out for the Konami rock game.

1107
01:01:11,664 --> 01:01:17,240
Rym: While I was watching people play the Guitar Hero, I overheard a conversation from the people who were next up to play.

1108
01:01:17,702 --> 01:01:20,320
Rym: And one guy turned to, I guess it was a girlfriend or someone.

1109
01:01:20,601 --> 01:01:24,120
Rym: It seemed like girlfriend because they were totally making kissy faces at each other.

1110
01:01:24,200 --> 01:01:33,940
Rym: But he basically said, I'm something to the effect of, we'll see how this plays out, because after Guitar Hero three, well, I don't know anymore.

1111
01:01:34,321 --> 01:01:35,059
Scott: Yeah, pretty much.

1112
01:01:35,421 --> 01:01:35,798
Scott: All right.

1113
01:01:36,724 --> 01:01:40,400
Scott: So there's in the way back of the exhibition hall, there was this Intel booth.

1114
01:01:40,461 --> 01:01:42,259
Scott: They basically had a trailer that you could go inside.

1115
01:01:43,021 --> 01:01:46,920
Rym: It was Intel Extreme Gaming, eight core monstrosities.

1116
01:01:47,120 --> 01:01:49,219
Rym: Check out the biggest, baddest things.

1117
01:01:49,440 --> 01:01:52,540
Scott: They had the craziest possible computers you could possibly get.

1118
01:01:52,600 --> 01:01:56,380
Scott: They were all Intel machines and they were all running all sorts of different games.

1119
01:01:56,600 --> 01:02:00,220
Rym: Now, this, you can make this shit up.

1120
01:02:00,501 --> 01:02:05,880
Rym: So we walk in and Scott stands in front of this kind of low powered like economy game.

1121
01:02:06,100 --> 01:02:07,040
Scott: It was like a fifteen hundred.

1122
01:02:07,140 --> 01:02:08,900
Scott: It said they had prices on all the machines.

1123
01:02:08,961 --> 01:02:11,060
Scott: It was like, here's a fifteen hundred dollar gaming machine.

1124
01:02:11,402 --> 01:02:14,839
Scott: So I got in front of it and I started playing whatever game was on there, some FPS.

1125
01:02:15,301 --> 01:02:18,660
Rym: And right next to it was the kind of the best machine they had.

1126
01:02:18,780 --> 01:02:20,880
Scott: This was like a four five thousand dollar game.

1127
01:02:21,001 --> 01:02:24,020
Rym: This was like this ludicrous gaming machine.

1128
01:02:24,220 --> 01:02:27,579
Rym: And we both hit, you know, start the game at the same time.

1129
01:02:28,480 --> 01:02:32,140
Rym: Scott's game loaded like ten times faster than mine.

1130
01:02:32,320 --> 01:02:34,100
Scott: My machine was just working just fine.

1131
01:02:34,580 --> 01:02:36,020
Rym: Mine was slow as shit.

1132
01:02:37,342 --> 01:02:40,060
Scott: Obviously, I'm not saying it's because of Intel hardware or anything like that.

1133
01:02:40,500 --> 01:02:41,780
Rym: Something was wrong with this demo.

1134
01:02:42,080 --> 01:02:44,300
Scott: Something was wrong with the software set up on the machine.

1135
01:02:44,500 --> 01:02:47,240
Scott: Maybe they had the software running two copies at once or something.

1136
01:02:47,280 --> 01:02:52,660
Rym: The fact that I was standing in front of what Intel is telling me is the best gaming machine money can buy.

1137
01:02:53,420 --> 01:02:54,459
Rym: And it really wasn't working.

1138
01:02:54,700 --> 01:02:56,060
Rym: Scott's in front of the economy.

1139
01:02:56,581 --> 01:02:58,520
Rym: Well, you can probably afford this one.

1140
01:02:58,680 --> 01:02:59,399
Rym: It was working great.

1141
01:03:00,040 --> 01:03:01,573
Scott: Yeah, it was just because the machine was set up.

1142
01:03:01,633 --> 01:03:02,420
Scott: poorly, obviously.

1143
01:03:02,581 --> 01:03:07,720
Scott: But it shows people running that booth weren't making sure the machines were reflecting their product well.

1144
01:03:08,160 --> 01:03:11,780
Rym: And of course, there was the voting and all the stuff for the Pax 10.

1145
01:03:11,780 --> 01:03:15,820
Rym: But I feel like we should talk about the Pax 10 after we have played all 10 Pax 10.

1146
01:03:15,820 --> 01:03:21,640
Scott: Basically, the deal is the Pax 10, they had a Pax themselves, right?

1147
01:03:21,780 --> 01:03:26,962
Scott: I guess Gabe and Tycho, I don't know, maybe some other people, picked 10 independent games that are the Pax 10.

1148
01:03:26,962 --> 01:03:30,180
Scott: And they had a booth there where you could play all of these 10 games.

1149
01:03:30,563 --> 01:03:32,280
Scott: And you could vote on which one was the best.

1150
01:03:32,543 --> 01:03:34,180
Scott: And the best one won something good.

1151
01:03:34,862 --> 01:03:37,680
Scott: And there were these 10 different indie games.

1152
01:03:38,182 --> 01:03:40,420
Scott: And we played a bunch of them, actually.

1153
01:03:40,700 --> 01:03:43,040
Scott: And some of them we didn't even realize are Pax 10 games.

1154
01:03:43,160 --> 01:03:48,140
Scott: And they were all, you know, the ones we played were all pretty interesting in one way or another.

1155
01:03:48,802 --> 01:03:51,500
Scott: And I guess we'll talk more about them in the future at some point.

1156
01:03:51,520 --> 01:03:57,000
Rym: Yeah, they definitely deserve a dedicated, at least a bit in a show, as opposed to an offhand mention here.

1157
01:03:57,100 --> 01:04:03,220
Scott: There was this one called Project Aftermath, though, that if we played that one the most of all of them, and Rym played it, actually.

1158
01:04:03,300 --> 01:04:08,380
Scott: And if they get the multiplayer on that game set up right, it could be something wicked awesome.

1159
01:04:08,380 --> 01:04:14,920
Rym: Yes, suffice to say, Project Aftermath is a game that I'm going to be watching with great interest.

1160
01:04:15,622 --> 01:04:18,560
Scott: I can't guarantee a winner, but it's something to keep your eye on.

1161
01:04:18,820 --> 01:04:25,440
Rym: If any game has a chance of pulling this kind of game off, and I point out that I've never seen a game pull this kind of game off.

1162
01:04:25,720 --> 01:04:27,258
Rym: I've seen very few people even attempt it.

1163
01:04:28,040 --> 01:04:31,140
Rym: Project Aftermath could be the game.

1164
01:04:31,460 --> 01:04:36,820
Scott: There was also a game that was made by a team of people from RIT, so go RIT.

1165
01:04:37,901 --> 01:04:45,280
Rym: Yes, but the one cool thing I want to mention about the exhibition hall is that it was up across this big skyway.

1166
01:04:45,780 --> 01:04:51,060
Rym: And you walk around outside the front of the con, there's this kind of big skyway above you, with glass windows and a glass roof.

1167
01:04:52,081 --> 01:04:56,660
Rym: That was like this hangout area between the exhibition hall and the rest of the con.

1168
01:04:57,240 --> 01:05:02,660
Rym: And there was cool stuff out there, like all the bands had their little booths to hang out there and meet after the concerts.

1169
01:05:03,783 --> 01:05:05,899
Rym: There were a whole bunch of sumos and just cool stuff.

1170
01:05:06,382 --> 01:05:11,080
Scott: Yeah, it was a good, nice and airy room that made it a comfortable space.

1171
01:05:11,380 --> 01:05:15,399
Scott: Like if you exited the exhibition hall, you could go "ahh" and not be crowded in.

1172
01:05:15,880 --> 01:05:18,519
Scott: And it made traffic in and out of the exhibition hall really smooth.

1173
01:05:19,160 --> 01:05:23,500
Scott: Whereas Otakon, where they're dealer's room, is sort of a narrow entryway and a narrow exit.

1174
01:05:23,801 --> 01:05:26,520
Scott: So they need to separate the entryway and the exit to keep it smooth.

1175
01:05:26,640 --> 01:05:32,160
Scott: But they were able to keep it smooth by just having a giant whole bunch of doors going into a giant empty room.

1176
01:05:32,721 --> 01:05:40,540
Rym: But all that aside, we did all these things and then eventually it comes around to 4 o'clock or so, we got ready to do our panel.

1177
01:05:41,280 --> 01:05:43,127
Scott: We had to do our Beyond D&D panel.

1178
01:05:43,268 --> 01:05:50,920
Scott: It was the same Beyond D&D panel we did at ConnectiCon, except I feel like we sort of ran out of material a little quickly.

1179
01:05:51,262 --> 01:05:52,279
Rym: I don't think so at all.

1180
01:05:52,720 --> 01:05:54,040
Scott: And we had to keep talking.

1181
01:05:54,260 --> 01:05:55,006
Rym: I don't think so at all.

1182
01:05:55,026 --> 01:05:56,840
Rym: We had another hour easily of material.

1183
01:05:57,101 --> 01:06:02,259
Rym: We had to cut everything off pointedly in order to say the bare minimum things we wanted to say.

1184
01:06:02,940 --> 01:06:04,040
Scott: I don't know about that.

1185
01:06:04,400 --> 01:06:09,960
Scott: I felt, because I was looking at the clock after we were starting to get towards the end of the slides, and we had like a half hour left.

1186
01:06:10,300 --> 01:06:13,820
Rym: Scott, at ConnectiCon, we got to the end of the slides at about the same point.

1187
01:06:14,001 --> 01:06:16,199
Rym: And then we just talked without slides for the rest of it.

1188
01:06:16,560 --> 01:06:16,823
Scott: Yeah.

1189
01:06:17,126 --> 01:06:17,852
Scott: Oh, it was alright.

1190
01:06:17,933 --> 01:06:18,720
Scott: It was a great panel.

1191
01:06:18,940 --> 01:06:21,014
Rym: In fact, it was paced almost the exact same way.

1192
01:06:21,054 --> 01:06:21,839
Rym: I don't know where you get this.

1193
01:06:23,001 --> 01:06:28,760
Scott: Anyway, it was actually the panel had this giant line forming, just as every other panel had a giant line forming.

1194
01:06:28,920 --> 01:06:34,060
Rym: Basically, most cons, we go to our panel room like five minutes before the panel, because we're doing a million panels.

1195
01:06:34,140 --> 01:06:36,211
Rym: But here at PAX, we only had one.

1196
01:06:36,231 --> 01:06:38,060
Rym: This was our only obligation.

1197
01:06:38,261 --> 01:06:41,216
Rym: So we got dinner, took a nap, got all prepared.

1198
01:06:41,256 --> 01:06:42,040
Rym: We came back over.

1199
01:06:42,822 --> 01:06:45,840
Rym: We walk over to the panel room a little over an hour before our panel.

1200
01:06:46,680 --> 01:06:51,040
Rym: And there are already a lot of people lined up for this panel.

1201
01:06:51,181 --> 01:06:55,840
Scott: I had a feeling like people were lining up for every panel at the con, and ours was not an exception.

1202
01:06:56,140 --> 01:06:58,311
Scott: People were definitely digging our panel.

1203
01:06:58,331 --> 01:06:59,396
Scott: You know, they read the description.

1204
01:06:59,416 --> 01:07:00,180
Scott: They saw the title.

1205
01:07:00,622 --> 01:07:02,171
Scott: They knew us for whatever reason.

1206
01:07:02,513 --> 01:07:03,520
Scott: They wanted to be there.

1207
01:07:03,862 --> 01:07:06,480
Scott: In fact, they ran it right after Art of the Dungeon Master.

1208
01:07:06,921 --> 01:07:14,540
Scott: And I think a lot of Art of the Dungeon Master people wanted to go to our panel also and couldn't, because they left that panel and then had to get in the line for ours immediately.

1209
01:07:15,081 --> 01:07:17,591
Scott: And some of them, you know, it just the room wasn't that big.

1210
01:07:17,631 --> 01:07:19,700
Scott: It would only seated like a hundred people, maybe.

1211
01:07:19,760 --> 01:07:29,660
Rym: It was kind of good, but also bad, because I feel like some of those WotC people from the previous panel might have wanted to be at our panel, because it was the WotC people talking about being a game master.

1212
01:07:29,740 --> 01:07:33,260
Rym: And then right after, some guys talking about why D&D is kind of poop.

1213
01:07:34,020 --> 01:07:34,141
Scott: Yeah.

1214
01:07:34,663 --> 01:07:37,375
Scott: I looked around online, you know, for feedback of our panel.

1215
01:07:37,395 --> 01:07:38,460
Scott: There was actually quite a bit.

1216
01:07:39,001 --> 01:07:46,959
Scott: And everyone was saying good things, but one guy said, "Yeah, you guys basically spent the whole time saying D&D sucks, but no, really, it

1217
01:07:46,999 --> 01:07:47,300
Scott: doesn't.".

1218
01:07:47,400 --> 01:07:49,048
Scott: Which we kind of did a little bit.

1219
01:07:49,108 --> 01:08:00,651
Scott: It's just we really tried to avoid doing that, but it's hard, because D&D is the reference point everyone has to go by, so you have to keep using it to compare to, and thus it seems like you're saying it's poop, but really,

1220
01:08:00,671 --> 01:08:01,233
Rym: we were

1221
01:08:01,273 --> 01:08:02,900
Scott: saying D&D isn't poop, it's different.

1222
01:08:02,960 --> 01:08:07,660
Rym: Well, what we said that it seems like most people got was that for role-playing, D&D really is poop.

1223
01:08:08,063 --> 01:08:08,280
Rym: Yeah.

1224
01:08:08,480 --> 01:08:10,939
Rym: If you want to role-play, there's no reason to use D&D.

1225
01:08:11,120 --> 01:08:14,720
Scott: Well, role-play as per the definition of role-playing, which we defined at the beginning of the panel.

1226
01:08:14,840 --> 01:08:21,120
Rym: If you want to role-play, as in play a role in a collaborative storytelling environment, D&D provides almost nothing for that.

1227
01:08:21,240 --> 01:08:21,620
Rym: But anyway.

1228
01:08:21,921 --> 01:08:22,538
Scott: Less than nothing.

1229
01:08:22,939 --> 01:08:28,899
Rym: That was our panel, and we did this panel, and the panel went over amazingly well.

1230
01:08:28,979 --> 01:08:30,580
Rym: We had Luke Crane and Jared Sorensen.

1231
01:08:30,640 --> 01:08:32,678
Scott: We had to get them in because they didn't show up early enough.

1232
01:08:33,020 --> 01:08:36,269
Rym: Yeah, basically, Luke Crane calls me, he's like, "Yeah, we're outside.

1233
01:08:37,112 --> 01:08:38,354
Rym: They're not going to let us in.

1234
01:08:38,395 --> 01:08:39,497
Rym: They're telling us that there's no

1235
01:08:39,578 --> 01:08:39,839
Rym: room.".

1236
01:08:40,180 --> 01:08:43,136
Rym: And I was like, I motioned to the staffer, and the staffer's like,

1237
01:08:43,156 --> 01:08:43,698
Rym: "Huh?".

1238
